[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 2:16-17",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Deuteronomy 2:16-17",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "When all the men of war were consumed — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Israel is not called to march against and attack the Canaanites till the men most fit for war, and who probably had learned the art of it in Egypt, and had been used to hardship, were ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "all wasted and dead from among the people, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and only a host of new raised men, trained up in a wilderness, were left, in whom, as being possessed of little knowledge, experience, or natural fortitude, no great dependance could be placed. Thus it became more fully manifest that ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the excellency of the power ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "which subdued the warlike Canaanites, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "was of God and not of man. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "On the same principle, and with the same design, long after this, were the following words spoken by the Lord to Gideon: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "The people that are with thee are too many for me to give the Midianites into their hands, lest Israel vaunt themselves against me, saying, Mine own hand hath saved me. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And thus, to subdue the enemies of God’s church, and bring sinners to the obedience of the faith, he ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "hath chosen the weak things of the world, and things that are despised, and things that are not, to bring to naught the things that are, that no flesh may glory in his presence.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "2:8-23 We have the origin of the Moabites, Edomites, and Ammonites. Moses also gives an instance older than any of these; the Caphtorims drove the Avims out of their country. These revolutions show what uncertain things wordly possessions are. It was so of old, and ever will be so. Families decline, and from them estates are transferred to families that increase; so little continuance is there in these things. This is recorded to encourage the children of Israel. If the providence of God has done this for Moabites and Ammonites, much more would his promise do it for Israel, his peculiar people. Cautions are given not to meddle with Moabites and Ammonites. Even wicked men must not be wronged. God gives and preserves outward blessings to wicked men; these are not the best things, he has better in store for his own children.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The words, \"said I,\" are not in the Hebrew. The words \"rise up, and get you over the brook Zered\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 21:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " note) connect themselves with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 2:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and form the conclusion of what God said to Moses. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "16. all the men of war were consumed and dead from among the people—The outbreak at Kadesh on the false report of the spies had been the occasion of the fatal decree by which God doomed the whole grown-up population to die in the wilderness [Nu 14:29]; but that outbreak only filled up the measure of their iniquities. For that generation, though not universally abandoned to heathenish and idolatrous practices, yet had all along displayed a fearful amount of ungodliness in the desert, which this history only hints at obscurely, but which is expressly asserted elsewhere (Eze 20:25, 26; Am 5:25, 27; Ac 7:42, 43).",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
